name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: Investors see the bad news as good news, anticipating Biden will deliver a large, potentially $2 trillion, stimulus package that'll reportedly include checks and state aid for vaccine distribution.  The Dow, Nasdaq and Russell 2000 are all at records.

name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: Last week jobless claims, continuing claims (the number of claims collected for more than one week), and the four-week average of new claims all rose.  December was the first month since April that the U.S. economy lost jobs on net, with 140,000 positions shed.

name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: More signs the recovery is in jeopardy: nearly one million Americans filed for first-time state unemployment benefits last week.   That's 965,000 Americans, to be exact.  Weighing:  ‚Ä¢ Cold weather ‚Ä¢ Surging covid cases ‚Ä¢ New, contagious strains ‚Ä¢ Fresh, extended restrictions

name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: Additionally, since the end of Dec., market participants have warned we're due for a pullback because of overexuberance in the market.

name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: Last week reports showed investors viewed the violent attack on the Capitol as an isolated event.   This week lawmakers fear there's more to come in D.C. and around the country ahead of Biden's inauguration.

name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: Stocks are set to retreat from their records as political pressure and economic uncertainties grow.   The House is set to move forward with impeachment of Trump, extremists call for more violence ahead of the inauguration and the fate of stimulus amid this hangs in the backdrop.

name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: Stocks rise to records despite a surprising loss of 140,000 jobs in December.   Rising covid cases, restrictions, the cold and delayed stimulus all weighed.  Still, investors are focused on the future, anticipating more fiscal relief.

name: Kristen Scholer
tweet: Investors are looking past the violent unrest in D.C. mid-week, with markets set to open at records.  Despite the coronavirus, a slowing recovery and politics, investors are focused on:  ‚Ä¢ A new presidential administration ‚Ä¢ The hope of more stimulus  ‚Ä¢ A tempered tax agenda
